booking = subset(booking, select = c(is_canceled,lead_time,arrival_date_month,stays_in_weekend_nights,stays_in_week_nights,adults,children,babies,meal,market_segment,reserved_room_type,customer_type,adr,total_of_special_requests))
library(faraway)
library(lmtest)

#Split data for training and test
sample_size = floor(0.8*nrow(booking))
train_ind = sample(seq_len(nrow(booking)), size = sample_size)
train = booking[train_ind,]
test = booking[-train_ind,]
library(faraway)
library(lmtest)

#run logistic regression model
g1=glm(is_canceled ~ lead_time +arrival_date_month+stays_in_weekend_nights+stays_in_week_nights+adults+children+babies+meal+market_segment+reserved_room_type+customer_type+adr+total_of_special_requests, data=train)

my1se.err = myCPtable[id.min,'xerror'] + myCPtable[id.min, 'xstd']
plotcp(kt)
abline(h=my1se.err, col="red") 

# The size.min approach: pick the tree size with the smallest CV error.
# this can be done by pruning your tree using a CP value between myCPtable[id.min, 'CP'] and  myCPtable[id.min-1, 'CP']

CP.min = (myCPtable[id.min, 'CP'] + myCPtable[(id.min-1), 'CP'])/2
tree.min = prune.rpart(kt, CP.min)
plot(tree.min,compress=T,uniform=T,branch=0.4,margin=.10)
text(tree.min,cex=0.5)

# The size.1se approach: pick the smallest tree below the red line
id.1se = min(which(myCPtable[,'xerror'] < my1se.err)) 
CP.1se = (myCPtable[id.1se, 'CP'] + myCPtable[(id.1se-1), 'CP'])/2
CP.1se
## [1] 0.04423328
